Specifying models

Let’s quickly re-review the broad-strokes facts in the /ay/ data.

ay <- ay %>% 
        mutate(dob = year-age,
               decade = (dob-1900)/10,
               log2dur = log2(dur),
               dur_c = log2dur - median(log2dur))

First, there seems to be some relationship between duration and F1:

ay %>%
  ggplot(aes(dur_c, F1_n, color = plt_vclass))+
    geom_point(alpha = 0.6)+
    facet_wrap(~plt_vclass)+
    stat_smooth(method = lm,
                color = "black")+
    theme_bw()

And there seems to be a relationship between decade and F1

ay %>%
  ggplot(aes(decade, F1_n, color = plt_vclass))+
    geom_point(alpha = 0.6)+
    facet_wrap(~plt_vclass)+
    stat_smooth(method = lm,
                color = "black")+
    theme_bw()

There are a number of open questions we are faced with when we approach this data from a modelling perspective:

  1. How do we decide which predictors to include in the model?
  2. How do we decide how they should be included in the model? Which predictorsshould we estimate interactions for?
  3. What should the random effects structure be?

To start trying to answer these questions, we need to start talking about model comparison. Let’s start by fitting a fairly complex model.

ay_big_mod <- lmer(F1_n ~ decade * dur_c * plt_vclass + 
                      (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass | idstring) +
                      (1 | word),
                    data = ay,
                    verbose = T)

Let’s interpret the model:

First, looking at the predictors without an interaction (i.e. the lines for elsewhere /ay/)

                            Estimate Std. Error t value
(Intercept)                 1.271174   0.021136   60.14
decade                     -0.015488   0.003354   -4.62
dur_c                       0.302195   0.019206   15.73
decade:dur_c                0.020117   0.003831    5.25

There is an effect of F1 decreasing as decade increases, and an effect of F1 increasing as duration increases (both observable in the figures above). But it also looks like that as the decades move on, the duration effect gets steeper.

Next, we can look for the effects that interact with voicing:

                            Estimate Std. Error t value
plt_vclassay0              -0.061892   0.036771   -1.68
decade:plt_vclassay0       -0.098273   0.005434  -18.08
dur_c:plt_vclassay0        -0.078575   0.026847   -2.93
decade:dur_c:plt_vclassay0 -0.002469   0.004903   -0.50

These effects are saying that /ay0/ starts out with a lower F1, and has a steeper decline in F1 over decade (both unsurprising). It’s also saying that the duration effect on /ay0/ is weaker (i.e. 0.30 -0.08 = 0.22), and the steepening effect that (might) exist for /ayV/ is weaker (i.e. 0.020 - 0.002 = 0.018).

When I look at these results, it seems obvious to me that we need to be taking into account the effect of decade and duration. But, I don’t have a good prior hypotheses for some of these interactions. Specifically,

  • I don’t know why the duration effect should get stronger over time.
  • I don’t know why the duration effect should be weaker for /ay0/.
  • I don’t know why the steepening effect should be weaker for /ay0/.

Looking at the three way interaction specifically, it has a very small effect size, and also a very small t value. Maybe it’s not contributing anything to the model. Let’s fit another model that is exactly the same, except it excludes that effect.

ay_smaller_mod <- lmer(F1_n ~ decade * dur_c * plt_vclass - 
                         decade:dur_c:plt_vclass +
                      (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass | idstring) +
                      (1 | word),
                    data = ay,
                    verbose = T)

One way we could try to evaluate which of these models is better is just to compare their root mean squared error. In case you’re hazy on how to calculate the RMSE, here’s a step by step breakdown of the code:

We can calcualte this for both models:

rmse_big <- sqrt(mean((ay$F1_n - fitted(ay_big_mod)) ^ 2))
rmse_smaller <- sqrt(mean((ay$F1_n - fitted(ay_smaller_mod)) ^ 2))

Then see which one is smaller.

rmse_big < rmse_smaller
[1] TRUE
rmse_smaller - rmse_big
[1] 2.545569e-06

The bigger model has a smaller RMSE (by a very little bit), meaning it is a better fit to the data. But is it worth having the additional ineraction parameter? It is almost always the case that any predictor you add to the data will improve the model fit to the data.

Overfitting

Mixed effects models, just like all other models, can be subject to “overfitting”. Here’s a really obvious example involving different smoothing line to the pre-voiceless /ay/ data.

They’re all some attempt to “model” the data. The straight line abstracts away from a lot of the detailed movement in the data to describe it all as just a straignt line. The curve abstracts less, and captures more of the variation in the data. The curvy curve is chasing every little blip in the data.

In some sense, the curvy curve is a better descrption of the data, and it definiltey results in a smaller root mean squared error. But it’s not necessarilly a better model of the data, in a few senses.

  1. By chasing fluctuations present in the sample, it will be less successful at predicting new observations from the population.
  2. As a model of the phenomenon of interest, it is putting too much stock into minor fluctuations.

At the same time, you also don’t want a model that is too simple, because you’ll wind up overlooking important explanatory or predictive factors.

This is also sometimes called the bias-variance tradeoff. A model with high bias is too simple, and underfits the data. A model with high variance is too complex, and overfits the data.

Model Comparison

The question we want to know is whether the additional complexity of the model is worth the improvement of the fit. There are a few approaches to making this kind of evaluation, which we’ll cover. For the time being, we’ll assume that we’re only comparing models that are properly nested. That is, one model has all of the same predictors and random effects structures as the other model, plus some. We can compare the goodness of fit of ay_big_mod and ay_smaller_mod using the anova() function. Now, when you use anova() on to LMEs, it is not doing an ANOVA. The function anova() has just become semantically bleached to mean “compare two models”.

anova(ay_big_mod, ay_smaller_mod)

refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)
Data: ay
Models:
ay_smaller_mod: F1_n ~ decade * dur_c * plt_vclass - decade:dur_c:plt_vclass + 
ay_smaller_mod:     (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass | idstring) + (1 | word)
ay_big_mod: F1_n ~ decade * dur_c * plt_vclass + (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass | 
ay_big_mod:     idstring) + (1 | word)
               Df    AIC    BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
ay_smaller_mod 19 152832 153009 -76397   152794                         
ay_big_mod     20 152834 153020 -76397   152794 0.2572      1      0.612

There’s a lot in here, let’s take it piece by piece:

This is just a reminder of which models you’re comparing. R is clever enough to do the model comparison in the right order (the more complex model is compared to the simpler model.)

The AIC and the BIC are metrics of model fit. They’re trying to quantify this balance between how well the models fit the data vs how complex they are. I’ve mentioned the the tradeoff between improving the model fit and trying to avoid overfitting, and these Information Criterions are one way of trying to quantify it. I have the formulas for the AIC and the BIC here, not because the actual math matters for us, but in order to do a contrastive analysis:

\[ AIC = 2k - 2\ln(\hat{L}) \]

\[ BIC = \ln(n)k - 2\ln(\hat{L}) \]

This is a classic example of having two competing metrics that are basically the same, but people have their preferences so we get both.

When you’re comparing models (even multiple models) using AIC and BIC, the models with the smallest AIC and BIC are the preferred ones. There isn’t an established difference in AIC and BIC which is considered a “significant” difference. Roughly speaking, AIC and BIC differences around 2 indicated a weak difference between two models, and as the difference grows, so does the strength of the preference for the model with the smaller AIC and BIC.

As we can see from the actual AIC and BIC differences in our two models, the AIC difference is only 2, but the BIC difference is 11. I would conclude that this indicates a preference for the smaller model.

This block of numbers is dedicated to the Likelihood Ratio Test (or LRT). It is a significance test for whether the more complex model significantly improves model fit. Some notes:

  • LRTs should only be carried out comparing “nested” models. That is, one model should have all the same parameters as the other, plus some.
  • LRTs should ideally be carried out on minimally contrasting models.
  • These are evaluating a “stepping up” of the model complexity.

How to actually go about doing model comparison.

When doing model comparison, my recommendation is to do it in a directed way. For example, I’ve felt a little suspicious of this decade:duration interaction. So, I’ve fit a third model that also removes the two way interaction between duration and decade.

ay_smaller_er_mod <- lmer(F1_n ~ decade * dur_c * plt_vclass - 
                         decade:dur_c:plt_vclass - 
                         decade:dur_c +
                      (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass | idstring) +
                      (1 | word),
                    data = ay,
                    verbose = T)

And now, we can compare all three models in one go:

anova(ay_big_mod, ay_smaller_mod, ay_smaller_er_mod)
refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)

ay_smaller_er_mod:     word)

According to the Likelihood ratio test, the two way interaction significantly improves the model fit, but the three way interaction doesn’t. The model with the two way interaction is strongly preferred by the BIC and the AIC compared to the model without it, but only weakly over the model with the three way interaction.

There are methods out there that allow you to automate this process of adding and removing predictors to see which model is most preferred, but I would recommend you not use them. First of all, automated step-up, step-down model selection has fallen by the wayside within statistics proper. Second, you should always have a reason for doing some model comparison or another.

Specifying models

When approaching how to build up a model (which predictors should be included or excluded), I would caution against “kitchen sink” models, or trying to trying to outsource your reasoning to an automated step-wise regression.

I’ll summarise Gelman & Hill’s (2006) recommendations here:

  • “Include all input variables that, for substantive reasons, might be expected to be important in predicting the outcome.”
    • Joe addendum: I think substantive reasons include “I have a good theory” and “Previous work has included these”.
  • “It is not always necessary to include these inputs as separate predictors-—for example, sometimes several inputs can be averaged or stunmed to create a ‘total score’ that can be used as a single predictor in the model.”
  • “For inputs that have large effects, consider including their interactions as well.”

Their recommendation for excluding a variable from a model is more nuanced. They say:

  • “If a predictor is not statistically significant and has the expected sign, it is generally fine to keep it in. It may not help predictions dramatically hut is also probably not hurting them.”
  • “If a predictor is not statistically significant and does not have the expected sign (for example, incumbency having a negative effect on vote share), consider removing it from the model (that is, setting its coefilcient to zero).”
  • “If a predictor is statistically significant and does not have the expected sign, then think hard if it makes sense.”
  • “If a predictor is statistically significant and has the expected sign, then by all means keep it in the model.”

Specifying a random effects structure

There is currently some debate about how to specify the random effects structure of mixed effects models. One proposal from Barr et al (2013) is to always fit a “maximal” model. That is, a model where all possible random intercepts & slopes are included. You basically “set it and forget it” (unless the model doesn’t converge!) For example, for the /ay/ model we’ve settled on, the maximal random effects would look like this:

ay_max_model <- lmer(F1_n ~ decade * dur_c +
                            dur_c * plt_vclass +
                            decade * plt_vclass +
                            (1 + dur_c * plt_vclass  | idstring) +
                            (1 + decade * dur_c | word),
                     data = ay,
                     verbose = T)
summary(ay_max_model)

The Bootstrap

If you want to get something p-value-like or confidence interval-like for the parameters in a mixed effects model, the people who have developed these techniques recommend bootstrapping. Bootstrapping is a very general purpose technique that sort of looks like it shouldn’t work.

Bootstrapping in Principle

Bootstrapping is a very general method for estimating our uncertainty about any given paremeter estimate. For example, let’s say that we had 8 randomly1 sampled heights of linguists in a class I taught, and we were interested in how noisy an estimate this is of the average height of linguists.

heights = c(a = 69, b = 75, c = 62, d = 62, e = 73, f = 71, g = 61, h = 64)
mean(heights)
[1] 67.125

One method statisticians have developed is the “bootstrap” estimate of uncertainty. The way that works is you first resample your sample, with replacement.

new_heights = sample(heights, replace = T)
new_heights
 b  h  h  h  a  h  c  d 
75 64 64 64 69 64 62 62

Some people’s heights have shown up more than once, and some none at all. Then, you take the mean

mean(new_heights)
[1] 65.5

And now, you do this hundreds and hundreds of times.

replicates <- (1:100000) %>%
                map(~sample(heights, replace = T))%>%
                map(mean)%>%
                simplify()
data_frame(replicates = replicates)%>%
  ggplot(aes(replicates))+
    stat_density(color = "black", alpha = 0.6)+
    geom_vline(xintercept = mean(heights))+
    theme_minimal()

The statisticians have set unto us that this is a sensible way to estimate uncertainty about the mean of our sample. As the bootstrap is to the sample, so the sample is to the population. We can use some very simplistic methods to get a confidence interval out of the boostraps, say by taking the center 95% interval from the sample:

quantile(replicates, prob = c(0.025, 0.975))
  2.5%  97.5% 
63.625 70.750

Basically, this means we’ve got a pretty lousy sample for trying estimate the average height of linguists. This 95% CI ranges from just a bit taller than the shortest people in the sample and just a bit shorter than the tallest, meaning that as far as we know with these 8 people, any one of them could be the average height.

sort(heights)
 g  c  d  h  a  f  e  b 
61 62 62 64 69 71 73 75

You can use bootstrap replication for any property of the sample, incidentally. For example, we could try to estimate the standard deviation of linguists’ heights using this method.

sd_replicates <- (1:100000) %>%
                map(~sample(heights, replace = T))%>%
                map(sd)%>%
                simplify()
data_frame(sd_replicates = sd_replicates)%>%
  ggplot(aes(sd_replicates))+
    stat_density(color = "black", alpha = 0.6)+
    geom_vline(xintercept = sd(heights))+
    theme_minimal()

Bootstrapping for Regression

NOTE!: I give a bunch of code to do bootstrap replication by hand here, but there is a pre-built function to use called bootMer().

Bootstrapping to get confidence intervals for regression paremeters works in a similar way, but implemented differently. For clarity’s sake, we’ll just look at the data from one speaker.

sp1 <- ay %>% 
          filter(idstring == idstring[1], plt_vclass == "ay") %>%
          select(F1_n, dur_c)
ggplot(sp1, aes(dur_c, F1_n))+
    geom_point()+
    stat_smooth(method = 'lm')

sp1_mod <- lm(F1_n ~ dur_c, data = sp1)
sp1_mod

Call:
lm(formula = F1_n ~ dur_c, data = sp1)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)        dur_c  
     1.1950       0.5956

With this model, every data point has three values associated with it:

  1. Its x value (in this case, its duration)
  2. Its fitted y value (in this case, its predicted F1)
  3. Its residual error (the difference between its observed F1 and and the predicted F1).

In order to get a bootstrap estimate of the intercept and slope here, you actually sample the residuals with replacement, add them to each point’s fitted value, and refit the model.

sp1$resid <- resid(sp1_mod)
sp1$fitted <- fitted(sp1_mod)
head(sp1)

As a reminder, here’s a plot of the observed duration values against the fitted F1 values.

ggplot(sp1, aes(dur_c, fitted))+
    geom_point()

To get back the original data, you need to add each data point’s residual error to the fitted value.

ggplot(sp1, aes(dur_c, fitted + resid))+
    geom_point()

In bootstrapping, you actually create a new set of residuals by sampling the existing residuals with replacement. Then you add these to the fitted values to get a new bootstrap replicate.

Now, we just need to collect up all of these re-fittings, and plot them.

lm_boot <- (1:1000)%>%
                map(~(sp1 %>% mutate(resid_samp = sample(resid, replace = T),
                                     F1_n = resid_samp + fitted)))%>%
                map(~(lm(F1_n ~ dur_c, data = .x)))%>%
                map(tidy)%>%
                bind_rows(.id = "id")
lm_boot %>%
  ggplot(aes(estimate))+
    stat_density(alpha = 0.6, color = "black")+
    facet_wrap(~term, scales = "free")+
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0)+
    theme_bw()

Bootstrapping LMEs

The specific way which boostrapping works for lmer models is different than for vanilla linear models (dealing with the random effects structure appropriately is complex), but fortunately we don’t need to write code to do that for us. The function bootMer() will do it for us.

bootMer(model, FUN = fixef, nsim, …)

  • model
    • the model you want to do bootstrapping on (can be a linear or other generalized linear mixed effects model).
  • FUN
    • The function you want to apply to each re-fit model. This will almost always be just fixef
  • nsim
    • The number of bootstrap simulations you want to do
  • ...
    • Additional optional arguments (e.g. what different kinds of bootstrapping you want to do, whether or not to use parallel processing).

~5 minute break

Run this code to do 5 bootstrap replications

ayT_bootstraps <- bootMer(ayT_simple_mod, 
                         FUN = fixef, 
                         nsim = 5,
                         verbose = T)

The somewhat annoying thing about bootstrapping is that it takes just as long to fit each replication as it does to fit the original model.

ayT_bootstraps <- bootMer(ayT_simple_mod,
                          FUN = fixef,
                          nsim = 5000,
                          verbose = T)

Each t* item corresponds to a fixed effect coefficient. They show up in the summary in the same order they did in the model summary:

fixef(ayT_simple_mod)

 (Intercept)       decade        dur_c decade:dur_c 
  1.21677373  -0.11403289   0.22123967   0.01872352

In the bootstrap summary, the original column corresponds to the original coefficient estimate from the model.

To get a confidence interval for these parameters, we need to use the boot.ci() function.

boot.ci(bootstrap, index, type = perc)

  • bootstrap
    • The bootstrap object
  • index
    • The index of the coefficient you want a confidence interval for
  • type
    • Unfortunately, there are many different ways of estimating a confidence interval from bootstrapped replicates, and not all of them work for a bootstrapped lme. I recommend type = "perc"

So to get the bootstrap confidence interval for the intercept, we’d give index=1.

boot.ci(ayT_bootstraps, index = 1, type = "perc")

BOOTSTRAP CONFIDENCE INTERVAL CALCULATIONS

boot.ci(boot.out = ayT_bootstraps, type = "perc", index = 1)

Intervals : 
Level     Percentile     
95%   ( 1.154,  1.277 )  
Calculations and Intervals on Original Scale

This confidence interval excludes 0, so we could call this a reliable effect.

To get the confidence interval for the interaction between duration and decade, you give it index = 4

boot.ci(ayT_bootstraps, index = 4, type = "perc")

95%   ( 0.0101,  0.0276 )  
Calculations and Intervals on Original Scale

This confidence interval also excludes 0.

P-values with lmeTtest

If you are ever stuck with a reviewer who demands p-values, there is a package, lmerTest that will provide pvalues in the summary of models. What it specifically does is use the Satterthwaite approximation to estimate the degrees of freedom.

library(lmerTest)
ayT_simple_mod_p <- lmer(F1_n ~ decade*dur_c + 
                         (dur_c | idstring) + 
                         (1|word), 
                       data = ayT)
